│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│    The verifier reports "Instruction does not dominate all uses!" for values  │
│ produced by:                                                                  │
│    - experimental.vp.strided.load                                             │
│    - masked.gather                                                            │
│    used as operands to llvm.vector.insert. This indicates the SLP vectorizer  │
│ emitted a use (vector_insert) at a point in the block that precedes the       │
│ definition(s) of the sub-vector producers (the vector loads/gathers),         │
│ violating SSA dominance.                                                      │
│                                                                               │
│    In this reproducer, SLP builds a vector by inserting sub-vectors produced  │
│ by vectorized loads (strided/gather). The vector_insert is emitted before     │
│ those sub-vectors are defined.                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│    The provided log shows that the verifier fails immediately after SLP runs. │
│ The broken IR includes:                                                       │
│    - %6 = call <4 x i16> @llvm.experimental.vp.strided.load...                │
│    - %4 = call <8 x i16> @llvm.vector.insert... %6                            │
│    and similarly for @llvm.masked.gather. The verifier error says the defs    │
│ (%6/%7) do not dominate their uses (the vector.insert calls). This directly   │
│ points to an insertion point ordering bug in SLP's code emission.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│    - Build of the final vector from sub-vectors happens in                    │
│ BoUpSLP::processBuildVector via ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize(), which  │
│ calls createInsertVector(...) to generate llvm.vector.insert or equivalent    │
│ shuffles.                                                                     │
│    - For gather nodes that stitch together already-vectorized subtrees        │
│ (CombinedEntriesWithIndices), SLP first vectorizes those subtrees by calling  │
│ vectorizeTree() for each combined entry (createBuildVector() does this        │
│ explicitly at lines ~17410-17414).                                            │
│    - The insertion point for the gather node is set via                       │
│ BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle(E) only with respect to E's own bundle     │
│ (lines ~16131+). It does not account for the last instruction in the bundles  │
│ of the combined subtrees.                                                     │
│    - vectorizeTree for each subtree uses its own InsertPointGuard and sets    │
│ insertion just after the last scalar in that subtree's bundle; vectorized     │
│ loads/gathers are therefore emitted at that position, which can be later in   │
│ the block than the gather's insertion point.                                  │
│    - After the subtrees are vectorized, control returns to the gather, and    │
│ the builder insertion point is restored to the gather's position (earlier).   │
│ Emitting vector_insert there causes the use-before-def: vector_insert uses    │
│ the sub-vector value produced by a load/gather that appears later in the      │
│ block.                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│    In short: setInsertPointAfterBundle(E) only considers E; for gather nodes  │
│ that insert sub-vectors from other entries, we must emit after the latest of  │
│ E and all combined entries to preserve dominance.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│    - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                    │
│    - Function: BoUpSLP::setInsertPointAfterBundle(const TreeEntry *E)         │
│    - Change: When E is a gather and has CombinedEntriesWithIndices, compute   │
│ the last instruction across E and all combined entries' bundles and set       │
│ insertion after the latest. This ensures that any sub-vector producers (e.g., │
│ masked gather, vp.strided.load) already dominate the subsequent               │
│ llvm.vector.insert that consumes them.                                        │
│                                                                               │
│    Patch (inserted after acquiring LastInst for E and before computing        │
│ LastInstIt):                                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│    --- before ---                                                             │
│    Instruction *LastInst = &getLastInstructionInBundle(E);                    │
│    assert(LastInst && "Failed to find last instruction in bundle");           │
│    BasicBlock::iterator LastInstIt = LastInst->getIterator();                 │
│                                                                               │
│    --- after ---                                                              │
│    Instruction *LastInst = &getLastInstructionInBundle(E);                    │
│    assert(LastInst && "Failed to find last instruction in bundle");           │
│                                                                               │
│    // If we are about to build a vector from sub-vectors (combined entries),  │
│    // ensure we emit after the latest contributing bundle to preserve         │
│ dominance.                                                                    │
│    if (E->isGather() && !E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices.empty()) {             │
│      for (const auto &P : E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices) {                    │
│        const TreeEntry *SubE = VectorizableTree[P.first].get();               │
│        Instruction *Cand = &getLastInstructionInBundle(SubE);                 │
│        if (LastInst->getParent() == Cand->getParent() &&                      │
│            LastInst->comesBefore(Cand))                                       │
│          LastInst = Cand;                                                     │
│      }                                                                        │
│    }                                                                          │
│                                                                               │
│    BasicBlock::iterator LastInstIt = LastInst->getIterator();                 │
│                                                                               │
│    This mirrors the existing PHI/landing pad handling that follows and keeps  │
│ debug location behavior. By selecting the latest bundle tail among E and its  │
│ combined sub-entries (when in the same block), subsequent inserts             │
│ (vector_insert/shuffles) will be placed after the definitions of the          │
│ sub-vectors (e.g., masked.gather/vp.strided.load).                            │
│                                                                               │
│    Rationale:                                                                 │
│    - vectorizeTree() of sub-entries runs before finalize emission in          │
│ processBuildVector(). Those nested calls insert their instructions at their   │
│ own post-bundle IP. By moving the gather emission IP to be after the maximum  │
│ of all bundle tails, we ensure defs precede uses. If both pick the same       │
│ position, the nested vectorizeTree inserted first; the gather inserts later,  │
│ thus keeping a valid order.                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│    The crash is due to a dominance violation when emitting llvm.vector.insert │
│ for gather nodes that insert sub-vectors produced by later-emitted vector     │
│ loads/gathers. Adjusting setInsertPointAfterBundle() to account for the       │
│ latest last-in-bundle across the gather and its combined entries ensures the  │
│ final vector build is emitted after all its sub-vector producers. This        │
│ preserves SSA dominance and fixes the verifier failure for both               │
│ vp.strided.load and masked.gather cases.                                      │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
